******
[2] Bunchy top and mosaic diseases, abaca - central provinces and Mindanao
Date: Sun 1 Feb 2009
Source: The Sunday Times (Manila) [edited]
<http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2009/feb/01/yehey/top_stories/20090201top5.html>


In 2007, the Philippines produced 60 000 tons of abaca fiber, known
commercially as Manila hemp. It is a major source of income to small
farmers and is grown on about 127 258 hectares [315 000 acres]. Many
abaca farms are ravaged by mosaic and bunchy top virus diseases.

Conventional breeding for disease resistance had been futile. The
Institute of Plant Breeding at the University of the Philippines --
Los Banos made a recent breakthrough in developing lakatan [cultivar]
banana resistant to bunchy top disease through irradiation.
Scientists believe virus-resistant abaca could be developed from these by 2012.

Disease-ravaged plantations can be rehabilitated by planting
disease-free seedlings.

[Byline: P Julian]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A number of viruses can affect the members of genus _Musa_, which
includes species and hybrids representing wild and cultivated
bananas, plantains (cooking bananas), and abaca (_Musa textilis_).

_Banana bunchy top virus_ (BBTV; genus _Babuvirus_) only affects
_Musa_ species and causes one of the most serious diseases of these
crops. It is transmitted by the banana aphid (_Pentalonia
nigronervosa_) but can also be spread with infected suckers and
tissue cultures. For more information on BBTV see ProMED-mail post
no. 20090127.0372 and links below.

While mosaic-like symptoms on _Musa_ species may be due to several
viruses (for example, _Banana mild mosaic virus_, _Banana bract
mosaic virus_, _Sugarcane mosaic virus_, and even _Banana streak
virus_), the term 'mosaic' in item 2 most likely refers to the
disease caused by certain strains of _Cucumber mosaic virus_ (CMV;
genus _Cucumovirus_) on _Musa_ species (this disease is also called
infectious chlorosis or heart rot). CMV is spread by several species
of aphids, mechanical means, with infected plant material, and has
also been reported to be seed transmitted in banana. For more
information on CMV see ProMED-mail post no. 20080505.1533.

Control of these viruses is difficult since aphid vectors and virus
reservoirs are widespread. Disease management may include removal of
inoculum, use of clean planting material, and use of
resistant/tolerant crop varieties for replanting. As reported above,
radiation (and other mutagens) may be used to increase spontaneous
mutation rates and enhance the chances that resistant mutants may
arise. These novel genes can then be introduced into commercial crop
varieties by traditional breeding methods.

